  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3518451319" />
    <a title="Chris Heim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21074352-chris-heim"><img alt="Chris Heim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1370578419p2/21074352.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3518451319?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris Heim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris Heim" href="/user/show/21074352-chris-heim">Chris Heim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3518451319" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7266113802666181861">COVID-19 created some unexpected, additional reading time this summer, and as a result, I ran through my newer book purchases relatively quickly. Because of this, I&apos;ve started delving into the long-neglected archives of books I&apos;ve purchased over the years, but never read. <br/><br/>In the case of this book, published in 2000, the timing for reading it is very ironic in its juxtaposition against the global pandemic and the related politicization of this (hopefully) once-in-a-lifetime kind of event. (It was</span>
  <span id="freeText7266113802666181861" style="display:none">COVID-19 created some unexpected, additional reading time this summer, and as a result, I ran through my newer book purchases relatively quickly. Because of this, I've started delving into the long-neglected archives of books I've purchased over the years, but never read. <br /><br />In the case of this book, published in 2000, the timing for reading it is very ironic in its juxtaposition against the global pandemic and the related politicization of this (hopefully) once-in-a-lifetime kind of event. (It was also noteworthy to me that it was published just before 9/11/01.)<br /><br />The gist of the book is that the media abuses its power in certain instances in cultivating an irrational level of fear in the general populous. Examples expounded upon include child abductions and airline safety (or supposed lack thereof). <br /><br />I think the book is a worthwhile read, but even at a slim 200 pages, it felt repetitive and as though it could have been condensed into a lengthy newspaper or magazine article. So while it was, at times, interesting, the feeling that the author was beating a dead horse before too long warrants this book no better three stars (I'd probably have given it 2.5 if that were an option.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="7266113802666181861" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


